&gt;&gt;&gt;@DataProvider(name = &quot;test1&quot;)
&gt;&gt;&gt;public Object[][] createData1() {
&gt;&gt;&gt;return new Object[][] {
&gt;&gt;&gt;new Object[] { &quot;Cedric&quot;, new Integer(36) },
&gt;&gt;&gt;new Object[] { &quot;Anne&quot;, new Integer(37)},
&gt;&gt;&gt;};
&gt;&gt;&gt;}
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;On the plus side, this approach is really, really simple. I&#39;m having
&gt;&gt;trouble following all the JUnit 4 parameterized discussions simply
&gt;&gt;because I don&#39;t feel comfortable with Java 5 annotations and generics
&gt;&gt;yet. I just haven&#39;t worked enough with these java 5 features that they
&gt;&gt;come to me naturally. By contrast, I can read this and see exactly what
&gt;&gt;it&#39;s doing. Good.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;On the minus side, I think this might be too simple. It seems to require
&gt;&gt;all the test parameters to be initialized up front. If the parameters or
&gt;&gt;their initialization code is large or expensive, this could be a
&gt;&gt;problem. I would prefer the parameters to be lazily initialized before
&gt;&gt;each test and torn down after each test. This could be done if this
&gt;&gt;method returned an Iterator rather than a static array. Any reason it
&gt;&gt;wasn&#39;t done this way?
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; For simplicity.
&gt; 
&gt; But I understand the need for lazy initializations, and it&#39;s also a feature
&gt; that has been requested for the creation of test classes themselves, which
&gt; TestNG doesn&#39;t support either (just like JUnit, TestNG creates all the test
&gt; classes upfront and then invoke the test methods on them, which doesn&#39;t work
&gt; well in the cases you outlined).
&gt; 
&gt; For that reason, I have indeed been considering an iterator factory for test
&gt; classes as well, which I proposed a few months ago in this thread:
&gt; 
&gt; http://forums.opensymphony.com/thread.jspa?threadID=1685&tstart=60
&gt; 
&gt; I reproduced the proposal below so you don&#39;t have to read the entire thread.
&gt; 
&gt; I am still thinking of implementing it at some point, along with Data
&gt; Provider iterators, but it does require some re-design in our code base and
&gt; the demand hasn&#39;t been too strong so far (you&#39;re not the first one to
&gt; request it, though).
&gt; 
&gt; --
&gt; Cédric
&gt; 
&gt; Okay, I think I see where you are getting at. You want continuation
&gt; factories :-)
&gt; 
&gt; You are correct that right now, it&#39;s a two-step process:
&gt; 
&gt; - All the factories are invoked and create all the test instances
&gt; - TestNG runs on all the created instances
&gt; 
&gt; which is potentially a problem if these instances consume a lot of
&gt; resources.
&gt; 
&gt; Your factory iterator suggestion makes sense to me.
&gt; 
&gt; We could have a new kind of factory that returns an iterator:
&gt; 
&gt; @Factory
&gt; public Iterator createTests() { ... }
&gt; 
&gt; and TestNG would basically do the following:
&gt; 
&gt; Iterator it = factory.createTests();
&gt; while (it.hasNext()) {
&gt; Object testInstance = it.next();
&gt; invoke TestNG on this testInstance
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; Then it&#39;s up to you to make sure that your test instances are only created
&gt; when needed.
&gt; 
&gt; How does this sound?
&gt; 
&gt; --
&gt; Cédric
